  "text": "For no good reason the city was made in seven concentric circles topped with a commemorative double statue of Beltelephon and his favorite concubine, whose name was either Nephritis the Obese or Phyllis.  In any case the final architectural effect was that of an Italian wedding cake.* *The historian Bocaraton notes that this may have been intentionally “emblematic of the crumbs inside.” –Bored of the Rings, Chapter IX: Minas Troney in the Soup I spent my mithril coin and got out of Dol Amroth and headed straight to Minas Tirith. In a previous post where I gushed some about Helm’s Deep and how impressive I found it a comment was left looking forward to my reaction to this great city  So here we are for that. I will say, from the outset, that Minas Tirith is like Helm’s Deep on steroids, with much of the implications of that as part of the package. Minas Tirith viewed from the surrounding fields Arriving in the city through the main gates finds you in a wide open area that continues around the city in semi-circle as the first of seven layers to the grandiose cake that is Minas Tirith. The main gates loom over you The first tier is defined by the external wall and the rise up to the second tier, the two separated by a wide concourse that runs the length of the semi-circle.  A wide ramp exists between each of the tiers, offset left and right of the main gate as described in the books, making for a serpentine journey if one seeks to climb to the heights of the city. The map of Minas Tirith One of the first quests you get on arrival in the city is to go speak to the guards at the top of each of the ramp.  As you do this you should absolutely be sure to also get the stable master location for each tier because one of the early realizations you are likely to have about the place is that it is annoying to navigate so any shortcut to getting around is worth 10x the silver they charge for the ride.  I just wish they gave each level a number.  I won’t be around here long enough to memorize the tier names and ranks. City Stable Routes from the Main Gate I went and did my run up the place. The ramps are spacious It is easy enough to ride a normal mount through the city, and you will likely want to.  Your mounted combat mount is also an option in the lower levels, but as you go further up the city the concourse between the lower and upper wall on each grows more and more narrow, until you get up to the fifth or sixth tier where there are parts where two grown men might have an issue walking side by side and the bends and twists make it likely you and your mount will get caught up in the scenery. The city is amazingly well crafted and alive with NPCs.  You can be the only player in the city and it feels quite alive in a way that other MMO towns and cities often do not.  From the top ring looking down you can see the buildings of the rings in a cascade down to the main wall. Looking down on the lower tiers And a lot of the buildings… more than one might reasonably expect… are fleshed out inside, often well beyond the meager needs of whatever quest you might be running.  You can go from the throne room, where the chair of the Steward of Gondor sits on the bottom step, to dining areas, inns, crafting halls, stables, training rooms, and other locations. The throne of the missing king and the steward’s chair There is even a room with a model of the city in it, which is a bit meta I suppose. Model of Minas Tirith It’s only a model. And, of course, the usual suspects show up. Working under a different name, eh G? And, you know one of the hobbits has to be around somewhere. See what offering up your sword got you It is all way over the top honestly, and pushes the edge of the games ability to render.  I was in a couple of lavishly appointed, fully populated buildings and the video became pretty choppy.  It wasn’t stressing the video card, which barely deigns to spin up its fans when I play LOTRO.  Rather, I think the client itself was barely up to the task. All of which is extremely impressive.  A pity there isn’t much interesting to do. I mean, you get the whole Pippin treatment from Bergil, the son of Beregond of the guards of the citadel.  Bergil must just stand by the front gate looking for suckers or some such, as he clearly has a routine worked up of places to visit and treats to obtain using you. I suppose if you like the quests in the Shire where you run around to different inns or whatnot, then the Minas Tirith quests are not so bad.  You root our fifth columnists and deal with a troupe of actors and mediate a dispute between Beregond and his brother.  But a lot of it is a transparent effort to make you go digging around the city… and while the city is impressive, the tasks quickly become tedious.  I mean, did I really need to go collect the dirty towels from the bath house of the citadel? Seriously, this was a thing And then there was the whole thing with the chicken, which is exactly the reason you need to keep the troops busy or they start coming up with stuff like… well. As God as my witness, I thought chickens could fly It is actually kind of far down to the main gate from up there on the prow of the ship that juts out through the middle of the city, a reminder that the king and his people came from Numenor over the sea. Still… it is a long way down I did as much of that as I could, balancing the tedium of so many “run across town and talk to a guy” quests with my sightseeing.  Eventually the tedium beat down my curiosity and I went back out the front gate and into the Pelennor.  That too is overwrought and over built. Out in the fortifications that have been overrun by the enemy But it has the advantage of being rife with orcs and easterlings and other servants of Sauron, with a series of quests dedicated to slaying them.  What else does a mysterious, heavily armed drifter with a history of violence really need?  Plus I need to get leveled up to trigger the battle of Pelennor so I can see that and then move on to Mordor. It is getting closer.  I can feel it.",
